Hey boys, I wanted to reopen the conversation about Hod potentially running with Bennett. The way I see it, losing two of us for next year is a bad idea for our student society as a whole. I have been thinking about this for a while, and I think that this is a good idea for a couple of reasons. First, you guys are both fourth year, more experience and more connections with teacher. Bennet, you are a god tier academic and you seem to be super involved in the more logistical side of the ECE program. Hod being SoCo is already pretty experienced at organizing events and getting people there. I also think that having an electrical and a computer representative as presidents is a very logical thing to do and will keep each other in check when making decisions that could affect everyone. 

If I am not mistaken, Callum also has another year here, and I also have more time and am willing to step back from the role. I still really want to be involved in ECESS and have lots to learn from you guys, and I would be super open to running with Callum. (even though we don't know each other yet we get a whole year next year haha) I don't know if this is something that seems doable for you guys, but I think this is the way that we can put the success of ECESS ahead of our own personal objectives.

Join Us as a Mentor or Judge at the Vancouver Space Apps Challenge 2024!

We're excited to host the NASA Space Apps Challenge at UBC on October 5th and 6th, 2024, and we're looking for professors, industry experts, and professionals to contribute their knowledge and experience to the event!

Mentors play a key role by providing guidance and expertise to participants. You‚Äôll support passionate innovators as they tackle global challenges in science and technology. Mentoring is low commitment, with no responsibilities beyond offering advice and encouragement during the event. You can even give a short talk on your expertise or share your experiences in the space industry, inspiring the next generation of problem solvers.

Judges will have the rewarding task of evaluating submissions to select the top teams that will advance to the global NASA competition. This involves reviewing project videos on the Space Apps platform during the week following the event, helping decide which innovations will represent Vancouver on the world stage.

This is an amazing opportunity to engage with the vibrant space innovation community, share your expertise, and inspire future leaders. Your participation can have a lasting impact, both locally and globally.

If you're interested in shaping the future of space exploration and technology, please consider joining us as a mentor or judge. We would love to have your support!
